Rini Varghese and Carolee J. Winstein¶

Abstract¶

Objective: The purpose of this study was to examine if motor performance of the ipsilesional (IL) hand varies directly with motor impairment and performance of the contralesional (CL) hand, and if this relationship differs based on the lesioned hemisphere.

Hypothesis:
A. The Null Hypothesis, wherein the relationship between contralesional impairment and ipsilesional performance is not modified by the side of stroke lesion (i.e., LHD or RHD).
B. Alternative Hypothesis 1, wherein IL deficits are related to CL impairment but only in LHD and RHD with severe impairment (e.g., UEFM < 34).
C. Alternate Hypothesis 2, wherein IL deficits are related to CL impairment but only in LHD and not in RHD.

Methods: Participants were 42 pre-morbidly right-handed chronic stroke survivors (left hemisphere damage = 21) with mild-to-moderate paresis (upper extremity Fugl-Meyer range: 19-59). Motor performance for both hands was quantified using the distal items of the Wolf Motor Function Test time-score (dWMFT) and were log- transformed to meet assumptions for statistical testing. The relationship between motor performance of IL and CL hands was assessed using the co-efficient of determination ($R^{2}$) and multiple linear regression.

Results: Contralesional arm, CL motor impairment, i.e. UEFM, and CL hand performance, i.e. dWMFT, were found to be significant predictors of motor performance of the IL hand ($β_{1} =$ -0.698 and $β_{1} =$ 0.827 respectively; $p$ < 0.0001 for both). Importantly, relationship between IL and CL hand was significantly modified by the side of stroke lesion (model adjusted $R^{2} =$ 0.26 and 0.42, respectively, $p <$ 0.05). In individuals with LHD, CL impairment explained 42% and CL hand motor performance explained 65% of the variance in IL hand motor performance ((unadjusted $p <$ 0.001 for both). However, this relationship was not statistically significant in individuals with RHD (unadjusted $R^{2}$ < 1% for UEFM and 9% for dWMFT, $p >$ 0.05).

Conclusions: The severity of contralesional deficits directly influences ipsilesional hand motor performance in those with LHD but not RHD. Compared with individuals with LHD, those with RHD preserve a motoric advantage for the ipsilesional dominant hand and also demonstrate a disproportionate disadvantage for the contralesional non-dominant hand. These finding demonstrate that the relationship between motor performance of the contralesional and ipsilesional arm depend on the hemisphere of stroke.

Interim Summary ¶

On an average, the 42 stroke survivors who participated in this study had moderate level of motor impairment (UEFM = 41.6), were approximately 60 years of age, 5.75 years post-stroke, and were predominantly male (74%). Welch t-tests were used to compare age, chronicity, and Upper Extremity Fugl-Meyer (UEFM) scores between LHD and RHD, whereas Chi-square tests was used to compare the proportion of females and males between the two groups.
There were no significant differences between LHD and RHD in the level of impairment, age, chronicity or the number of males.

Step 2: Pre-Checks for Inferential Statistics ¶

Checking Normality of Continuous Predictor and Response Variables¶

All continuous variables were assessed for normality using Lilliefors test (modified Kolmogorov-Smirnov test). Distributions for chronicity and average distal WMFT time-score were negatively skewed, and were log-transformed. All continuous variables were standardized to unit variance (i.e., z-scored) for linear regression analysis.

Age is significantly related to Chronicity
As we see below, age was significantly related to chronicity. This is not surprising, because chronicity is embeded in age, as a construct. That is, as people age with stroke they also become more chronic. So in fact, we do expect these to be related.

Age is also significantly related to CL dexterous performance
As we see below, age is also significantly correlated with CL dexterous performance, which is expected as well. The fact that we are able to pick up age-related performance deficits using the dWMFT is pretty impressive. However, in the case of our model building, we must exercise caution. More on this is in the Interim Summary for this section.

Interim Summary ¶

It is important to note that: age in the same model with either of these two would render one or all of the variables non-significant. Additionally, because UEFM and CoDistAvg were significantly correlated, the two cannot be included in the same model when evaluating their relationship with IpDistAvg. This is not our intention or the purpose of our analyses, anyway, and is why we use two separate models. That is, Model 1 with UEFM as the main predictor along with SOL, and Model 2 with CoDistAvg as the main predictor along with SOL.

Multiple Linear Model¶

Model 0 Full: $\;\;$ CoDistAvg $= β_{0} +\; β_{1}$ (UEFM) $ + \;β_{2}$ (SoL) $ + \;β_{3}$ (UEFM x SoL) $ + \; β_{4}$ (Age) $+ \; β_{5}$(Sex) $+\; β_{6}$(Chronicity)$ \;+ \;\epsilon $

Model 0 Reduced: $\;\;$ CoDistAvg $= β_{0} +\; β_{1}$ (UEFM) $ \;+ \;β_{2}$ (SoL) $ + \;β_{3}$ (UEFM x SoL) $ + \;β_{4}$ (Age) $+ \; β_{5}$(Sex) $\; +\; \epsilon $

Hypotheses:
$\: \:$ $H_{0}: β_{1} = 0\;$
$\: \:$ $ H_{1}: β_{1} ≠ 0\; $

Comparing the Full and Reduced Models:
We begin with a full model in which we include age, sex, chronicity, uefm, and side of lesion (as well as our hypothesized interaction term), all as predictors. Then, we remove those predictors that don't satisfy the p = 0.2 lenient criteria. Below are logical outputs from the full model, for those coefficients which meet this liberal cut-off. That is, the predictors for which the value is TRUE are those that the p-value cut-off was met. These predictors were included in the final reduced model.

Thorndike Type-2 Corrections¶

Next, we use Thordike type 2 corrections to correct for range restrictions in UEFM measure of RHD. We use the entire sample's variance (i.e., standard deviation) to specify the unrestricted range.

$ R = \frac {r\frac{S}{s}} {\sqrt {1-r^2 \;+\; r^2(\frac {S^2}{s^2})}} $¶

$r_{s}$ = observed correlation between CL UEFM and IL dWMFT in the restricted sample
$s$ = estimated SD of CL UEFM in the RHD
$S$ = estimated SD of CL UEFM in the full sample
$R$ = estimated corrected correlation in the unrestricted sample when only the restricted sample has been used

In [24]:
tdike_r = rangeCorrection(cor(z.uefm[sol=="RHD"],zln.IpDistAvg[sol=="RHD"]),
                          sd(uefm[sol=="RHD"]),sd(uefm))
display_markdown(paste("We find that the Thorndike-corrected correlation for RHD is:",round(tdike_r,digits = 3)))

Multiple Linear Model¶

Model 1 Full: $\;\;$ IpDistAvg $= β_{0} +\; β_{1}$ (UEFM) $ + \;β_{2}$ (SoL) $ + \;β_{3}$ (UEFM x SoL) $ + \; β_{4}$ (Age) $+ \; β_{5}$(Sex) $+\; β_{6}$(Chronicity)$ \;+ \;\epsilon $

Model 1 Reduced: $\;\;$ IpDistAvg $= β_{0} +\; β_{1}$ (UEFM) $ + \;β_{2}$ (SoL) $ + \;β_{3}$ (UEFM x SoL) $ + \; β_{4}$(Sex) $\; +\;\epsilon $

Hypotheses:
$\: \:$ $H_{0}: β_{1} = 0\;$ & $\;β_{3} = 0.$
$\: \:$ $ H_{1}: β_{1} ≠ 0\;$ & $ \;β_{3} ≠ 0. $

Note: $\;β_{3}$ is the interaction effect that we seek to test. This is the main hypothesis of this paper.

Comparing the Full and Reduced Models:
We begin with a full model in which we include age, sex, chronicity, uefm, and side of lesion (as well as our hypothesized interaction term), all as predictors. Then, we remove those predictors that don't satisfy the p = 0.2 lenient criteria. Below are logical outputs from the full model, for those coefficients which meet this liberal cut-off. That is, the predictors for which the value is TRUE are those that the p-value cut-off was met. These predictors were included in the final reduced model.

Interim Summary ¶

The final reduced form of Model 2 was statistically different from a null model ($F = $11.04, p < 0.001, adjusted $R^{2}=$ 0.42). Based on estimates from this model, CL hand motor performance (dWMFT) was significantly associated with IL hand motor performance ($β_{1} =$ 0.83 ± 0.15, p < 0.001).
